        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Central Asian countries, primarily Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan, are preparing for the increasing demand for critical minerals. The IEAâ€™s Global Critical Minerals Outlook 2025 highlights <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-31-may-25-analysis-h1-1-central-asia-s-potential?source=website" target="_blank">Central Asia's potential</a> to meet the demand for lithium, cobalt, nickel, and rare earth elements. Lithium demand rose by 30% in 2024, with cobalt, nickel, and other rare earths also experiencing strong growth.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
         Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan are capitalizing on geopolitical shifts and their resource wealth to enhance their market positions. Kazakhstan, the leading uranium exporter, has benefited from the disruption of Russian trade, while Uzbekistan is in confidential talks with the US over critical mineral extraction.
            </p>
          
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;filter:blur(5px);">
         The growing influence of Central Asian states could help diversify sources. However, they face challenges like poor infrastructure and a lack of transparency. International partnerships are essential for these countries to become reliable alternatives.
            </p>
